@@eThe Priest Tradition@@N

@@yThe Hour of Quiet Thunder@@N
On a morning the records describe as unnaturally still, a faction of senior clerics
assembled in Midgaard's primary registry shrine and stated their position. The
tradition's civic function had diluted faith's purpose. Practitioners were registry
officials with religious credentials. Combat theology had produced effective support
fighters but diminished the healing arts the Dawn Liturgists had originally
developed. These purists withdrew from administrative work and combat theology,
devoting themselves entirely to restoration, consecration, and the slow patient
work of keeping the living alive.

@@yThe Ward-Networks@@N
The Priest tradition's most significant achievement is the great ward-networks:
systems of consecrated shelter distributed across the old cities that protect
travelers and pilgrims against undead, cursed entities, and corrupted magical
phenomena. Ward-network maintenance is unglamorous work requiring constant renewal
of seals, inspection of physical anchors, and managing relationships with the
communities that house them. A network maintained properly is invisible; it prevents
problems without evidence that it prevents anything. Recognition flows to those who
solve dramatic crises rather than those who prevent them, a dynamic the tradition
has never fully resolved.

@@yThe Healing Arts@@N
Priests have developed healing methodology to a degree of sophistication no other
tradition approaches, with systematic methods for compound conditions, delayed
progression injuries, and spiritually contaminated wounds. The most demanding
specialty is sustained miracle-channel operation: maintaining continuous healing
output over hours or days when conventional treatment has failed. A Priest
sustaining a channel is substantially less able to defend themselves, which is why
the Paladin-Priest partnership became the preferred operational model.

@@yDirect Service as Purpose@@N
The Priest tradition holds that direct service to suffering is not a lesser
application of divine power than cosmic containment maintenance. It is its ultimate
expression. The Solar Court's machinery was a response to a specific crisis; the
underlying purpose was to protect the living, and that purpose is best served
directly. Critics within the tradition argue that this ethic produces practitioners
who drain themselves beyond sustainable limits, but the founding impulse of the
Hour of Quiet Thunder makes the tradition culturally resistant to such caution.
